doctype html
html
  head
    link(href='//maxcdn.bootstrapcdn.com/bootswatch/3.3.5/darkly/bootstrap.min.css', rel='stylesheet')
    meta(name="viewport",content="width=device-width,height=device-height,white-space:normal, initial-scale=1.0")
  body
    div.navbar.navbar-default
      div(style='text-align:center; color: #FFFFFF')
        h1 iErgo
    div.container
      div.jumbotron(style='text-align:center')
        h1(style='text-align:center')#header
          | ACGIH® TLV® for Hand Arm Segmental Vibration
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
                | Purpose:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | To provide recommendations for hand-arm vibration exposure limits through a combination of frequency-weighted, RMS, component accelerations, and vibration
              | exposure duration.
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Developed by:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | TLV adopted by American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists from ISO 5349 and ANSI S3.34-1986
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Developed When:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | 1984-2004
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Musculoskeletal Disorder Risk Factors Considered:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Vibration
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Body Regions Considered:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Hands, arms, shoulders
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Type of Jobs Appropriate For:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Jobs requiring hand-held vibrating tools
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Type of Jobs Not Appropriate For:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Whole body vibration jobs and jobs without vibration
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Limitations:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Limited to hand vibration Ignores other MSD risk factors
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Inputs:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Cycle Time Orthogonal components of vibration provided transducer
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Outputs:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Comparison of hand activity to the Threshold Limit Value (TLV) for hand vibration
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Who is the Tool Design For:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Professionals trained in ergonomics, above a novice
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Minimal Amount of Training:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | High level of training and expertise required to identify vector directions, install lightweight measurement transducer, properly use low pass mechanical
              | filter, interpret results, including frequency weightings of vibration and advanced mathematic calculations.
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Studies That Provide Evidence of Validation of the Tool:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | None currently found in literature
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Electronic Version:
            panel-body
            h4 
              a(href='http://personal.health.usf.edu/tbernard/HollowHills/HAV50.xls') Hand-Arm Vibration Analysis
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Reference of Peer-Reviewed Publication:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | None currently found in literature
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Industries and Jobs Where Tool Has Been Applied:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Grinding, sanding, chipping, drilling, sawing, production using vibrating or power hand tools, regular use of vibrating hand tools
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Is Tool Copyrighted:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Yes, purchase price of $60 (2009) for ACGIH Threshold Limit Value guide
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Instructional or Supplemental Information:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | ISO 5349 and ANSI S3.34-1986:
              br
              | Both describe how to measure and evaluate human exposure to hand transmitted vibration
              br
              br
              | Threshold Limit Values for Chemical
              | Substances and Physical Agents & Biological Exposure Indices, (2009), American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists, 185-188.
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Equipment Needed to Use Tool:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | Small and lightweight transducer mounted to accurately record one or more orthogonal components of source vibration in the 5-1500 Hz range
              | Frequency-weighted filter network needed for human response measuring
        div.panel.panel-info
            h2(style='text-align:center')
              | Time Required Analyzing Typical Job:
            panel-body
            h4 
              | 8 hours
        br
        p(style='text-align:left')
          a.btn-lg.btn-danger(href="/tool_definitions") Back

